This article is a fact sheet from the White House Office of the Press Secretary about U.S.-African cooperation on global health. The United States has been investing in the health of Africa's people for decades and is committed to working with African governments to improve their citizens' health. The article highlights the progress that has been made in Africa's health over the past 20 years, including reductions in HIV, tuberculosis, and malaria deaths, as well as improvements in maternal and child health. However, there are still challenges to be addressed, such as new HIV infections, malaria cases, and child deaths. The article also discusses the U.S.'s commitment to achieving an AIDS-free generation, improving global health and child survival, and accelerating action to prevent, detect, and respond to infectious diseases. It mentions various initiatives and partnerships, such as the President's Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief (PEPFAR), the Global Health Security Agenda (GHSA), and efforts to combat non-communicable diseases (NCDs) and neglected tropical diseases (NTDs). The article concludes by highlighting the U.S.'s commitment to supporting Africa in various areas, including vaccines, tuberculosis detection and treatment, meningitis prevention, innovations in medical education, and applying genomics research to disease burdens in Africa.